f name=climate>{{cite web\n| url = http://extras.springer.com/2007/978-1-4020-4577-6/Book_Shahin_ISBN_9781402045776_Appendix.pdf\n| title = Appendix I: Meteorological Data\n| publisher = Springer\n| accessdate = 17 October 2016}}</ref> Meteo Climat (record highs and lows)<ref name = meteoclimat>\n{{cite web \n| url = http://meteo-climat-bzh.dyndns.org/index.php?page=stati&id=1153\n| title = Station Biskra\n| publisher = Meteo Climat \n|language = French \n| accessdate = 17 October 2016}}</ref>\n|date=September 2012\n}}\n\n===Flora and Fauna===\n[[File:Biskra Wild.jpg|thumb|left|A Giant Canyon at proximity of Biskra]]\n\n[[File:Vip\u00e8res \u00e0 cornes.jpg|thumb|right|The Horned Viper]]\n\nThe fauna of Biskra is characterised by a great diversity where insects such as [[Scarabaeus sacer|Sacred Scarab]] or yellow broad-tailed [[scorpion]] are found. There are also amphibians like the Frog, reptiles like the [[Horned Viper]] or the [[Egyptian cobra]]. A variety of birds including Black Warbler, mammals such as [[Gazelle]]s, small Gerboise, Fox, [[Wild boar]], [[Hare]], [[Hedgehog]], [[Bat]], [[Myriapoda|Myriapods]], Crustaceans such as the Crab stream or the [[Water Flea]]. There are also a lot of black and red spiders that some species hide in dead tree stumps.\n\n==Demographics==\n===Population===\n{| class=wikitable\n|+ Historical population\n! Year !! Population<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.populstat.info/Africa/algeriat.htm|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160303175036/http://www.populstat.info/Africa/algeriat.htm|url-status=dead|title=ALGERIA: urban population|archivedate=3 March 2016|website=www.populstat.info}}</ref>\n|-\n| 1901 || 7,500\n|-\n| 1911 || 20,000\n|-\n| 1926 || 22,000\n|-\n| 1931 || 18,900\n|-\n| 1936 || 21,300\n|-\n| 1948 || 36,400\n|-\n| 1954 || 52,500\n|-\n| 1966 || 59,300\n|-\n| 1977 || 77,000 (town)<br>90,500 (municipality)\n|-\n| 1987 || 128,300\n|-\n| 1998 || 177,600\n|-\n| 2010 || 300,000\n|}\n\n==References==\n*{{MW 1935|date=August 2008}}\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category-inline}}\n{{EB1911 poster|Biskra}}\n* {{in lang|fr}} [https://web.archive.org/web/20110511151334/http://www.eden-algerie.com/  Biskra City]\n\n{{Biskra Province}}\n{{Province seats of Algeria}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Cities in Algeria]]\n[[Category:Communes of Algeria]]\n[[Category:Oases of Algeria]]\n[[Category:Populated places in Biskra Province]]\n[[Category:Province seats of Algeria]]\n", "name_user": "Glottran", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eClimate:ditto here, formal English.", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Biskra"}
{"title_page": "Christine Ann Denny", "text_new": "{{short description|American neuroscientist}}\n{{cleanup|reason=duplicate refs, [[WP:NAMEDREFS]] are needed.|date=April 2020}}\n'''Christine Denny''' is an American neuroscientist and Associate Professor of Clinical Neurobiology in Psychiatry in the Department of Psychiatry at [[Columbia University]] Irving Medical Center in New York City. Denny investigates the molecular mechanisms underlying learning and memory is well known for her development of a novel technique to label neurons that encode specific memories. She uses this technique to probe what happens to [[Hippocampus|hippocampal]] memory traces in different disease states. {{Infobox scientist\n| name              = Christine Ann Denny\n| image             = \n| image_size        = \n| caption           = \n| birth_date        = \n| birth_place       = \n| nationality       = American\n| fields            = Neuroscience\n| workplaces        = Columbia University\n| alma_mater        = Boston College\n| known_for         = ArcCreERT2 transgenic mouse line for memory tracing\n| awards            = NIH Early Independence Award, ELabNYC Fellow, Inductee into the Lyndhurst High School Academic Hall Of Fame, Brain & Behavior Research Foundation NARSAD Young Investigator Award, American Society for Neurochemistry Travel Award, Molecular and Cellular Cognition Society Young Travel Fellowship\n| Institutions      = Columbia University\n}}\n\n== Early Life and Education ==\nDenny grew up in New Jersey and attended Lyndhurst High School.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.lyndhurstschools.net/1/Content2/20806|title=Lyndhurst High School|website=www.lyndhurstschools.net|access-date=2020-04-05}}</ref>\u00a0Denny excelled in her academic pursuits in high school and received multiple scholarships, was recognized for her leadership at the state level, and graduated as class [[Salutatorian]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.lyndhurstschools.net/1/Content2/20806|title=Lyndhurst High School|website=www.lyndhurstschools.net|access-date=2020-04-05}}</ref> Denny was also actively involved in athletics and received varsity letters in volleyball and track and field.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.lyndhurstschools.net/1/Content2/20806|title=Lyndhurst High School|website=www.lyndhurstschools.net|access-date=2020-04-05}}</ref>\n\nAfter graduating from Lyndhurst in 2001, Denny then pursued her undergraduate studies at [[Boston College]] where she received a Bachelors of Science majoring in Biological Sciences and minoring in Theology.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.lyndhurstschools.net/1/Content2/20806|title=Lyndhurst High School|website=www.lyndhurstschools.net|access-date=2020-04-05}}</ref> While at Boston College, Denny continued to excel in academics as she maintained Honor and Dean\u2019s List standing but she also became interested in research and received an Advanced Undergraduate Research Fellowship to support her research. In 2004, Denny began roles as a teaching assistant and laboratory instructor at Boston College.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.lyndhurstschools.net/1/Content2/20806|title=Lyndhurst High School|website=www.lyndhurstschools.net|access-date=2020-04-05}}</ref> After she graduated in 2005, Denny continued in academia pursuing a Masters in Biology at Boston College.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://portlandpress.com/neuronalsignal/pages/Editorial_board|title=Editorial Board|website=portlandpress.com|access-date=2020-04-05}}</ref> While at Boston College, Denny worked under the mentorship of [[Thomas N. Seyfried]] studying lipid storage diseases and metabolic therapies to treat brain diseases.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bc.edu/bc-web/schools/mcas/departments/biology/people/faculty-directory/thomas-seyfried.html|title=Thomas N. Seyfried - Biology - Morrissey College of Arts and Sciences - Boston College|website=www.bc.edu|language=en|access-date=2020-04-05}}</ref> In 2007, Denny published a first author paper in the Journal of Neurochemistry highlighting a model system for assessing retinal pathobiology and therapies for [[ganglioside]] storage diseases.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Denny|first=Christine A.|last2=Alroy|first2=Joseph|last3=Pawlyk|first3=Basil S.|last4=Sandberg|first4=Michael A.|last5=D\u2019Azzo|first5=Alessandra|last6=Seyfried|first6=Thomas N.|date=2007|title=Neurochemical, morphological, and neurophysiological abnormalities in retinas of Sandhoff and GM1 gangliosidosis mice|url=https://onlinelibrary.wiley.com/doi/abs/10.1111/j.1471-4159.2007.04525.x|journal=Journal of Neurochemistry|language=en|volume=101|issue=5|pages=1294\u20131302|doi=10.1111/j.1471-4159.2007.04525.x|issn=1471-4159}}</ref> Denny also explored lipid abnormalities in mouse models of [[Rett syndrome|Rett Syndrome]]<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Seyfried|first=Thomas N.|last2=Heinecke|first2=Karie A.|last3=Mantis|first3=John G.|last4=Denny|first4=Christine A.|date=2008-11-11|title=Brain Lipid Analysis in Mice with Rett Syndrome|url=https://doi.org/10.1007/s11064-008-9874-7|journal=Neurochemical Research|language=en|volume=34|issue=6|pages=1057|doi=10.1007/s11064-008-9874-7|issn=1573-6903|pmc=PMC4286142|pmid=19002580}}</ref> as well as the effects of\u00a0 ketogenic diets on alleviating symptoms of [[Sandhoff disease]], a ganglioside storage disease.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Denny|first=Christine A.|last2=Heinecke|first2=Karie A.|last3=Kim|first3=Youngho P.|last4=Baek|first4=Rena C.|last5=Loh|first5=Katrina S.|last6=Butters|first6=Terry D.|last7=Bronson|first7=Roderick T.|last8=Platt|first8=Frances M.|last9=Seyfried|first9=Thomas N.|date=2010|title=Restricted ketogenic diet enhances the therapeutic action of N-butyldeoxynojirimycin towards brain GM2 accumulation in adult Sandhoff disease mice|url=https://onlinelibrary.wiley.com/doi/abs/10.1111/j.1471-4159.2010.06733.x|journal=Journal of Neurochemistry|language=en|volume=113|issue=6|pages=1525\u20131535|doi=10.1111/j.1471-4159.2010.06733.x|issn=1471-4159}}</ref>\n\nDenny then pursued a PhD in neuroscience at [[Columbia University]] under the mentorship of Dr. Rene Hen.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.columbiamedicinemagazine.org/features/spring-2014/optogenetics-revolution|title=The Optogenetics Revolution|last=cmm_admin|date=2014-06-01|website=Columbia Medicine Magazine|language=en|access-date=2020-04-05}}</ref> Denny first explored hippocampal neurogenesis and published a first author paper in 2010 showing that inhibiting neurogenesis increases novel object exploration and impairs one trial contextual fear-learning in mice suggesting an important role for adult born neurons in cognitive function.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Denny|first=Christine A.|last2=Burghardt|first2=Nesha S.|last3=Schachter|first3=Daniel M.|last4=Hen|first4=Ren\u00e9|last5=Drew|first5=Michael R.|date=2012|title=4- to 6-week-old adult-born hippocampal neurons influence novelty-evoked exploration and contextual fear conditioning|url=https://onlinelibrary.wiley.com/doi/abs/10.1002/hipo.20964|journal=Hippocampus|language=en|volume=22|issue=5|pages=1188\u20131201|doi=10.1002/hipo.20964|issn=1098-1063|pmc=PMC3193906|pmid=21739523}}</ref> Denny then began to exploring the idea of memory traces, cells in the brain where memories are stored, and tried to tag these memory traces in the dentate gyrus and C3 regions of the hippocampus.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Denny|first=Christine\u00a0A.|last2=Kheirbek|first2=Mazen\u00a0A.|last3=Alba|first3=Eva\u00a0L.|last4=Tanaka|first4=Kenji\u00a0F.|last5=Brachman|first5=Rebecca\u00a0A.|last6=Laughman|first6=Kimberly\u00a0B.|last7=Tomm|first7=Nicole\u00a0K.|last8=Turi|first8=Gergely\u00a0F.|last9=Losonczy|first9=Attila|last10=Hen|first10=Ren\u00e9|date=2014-07-02|title=Hippocampal Memory Traces Are Differentially Modulated by Experience, Time, and Adult Neurogenesis|url=http://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/S0896627314004048|journal=Neuron|language=en|volume=83|issue=1|pages=189\u2013201|doi=10.1016/j.neuron.2014.05.018|issn=0896-6273}}</ref> She was able to develop a genetic tool that enabled her to fluorescently tag neurons that were activated in specific memories.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Denny|first=Christine\u00a0A.|last2=Kheirbek|first2=Mazen\u00a0A.|last3=Alba|first3=Eva\u00a0L.|last4=Tanaka|first4=Kenji\u00a0F.|last5=Brachman|first5=Rebecca\u00a0A.|last6=Laughman|first6=Kimberly\u00a0B.|last7=Tomm|first7=Nicole\u00a0K.|last8=Turi|first8=Gergely\u00a0F.|last9=Losonczy|first9=Attila|last10=Hen|first10=Ren\u00e9|date=2014-07-02|title=Hippocampal Memory Traces Are Differentially Modulated by Experience, Time, and Adult Neurogenesis|url=http://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/S0896627314004048|journal=Neuron|language=en|volume=83|issue=1|pages=189\u2013201|doi=10.1016/j.neuron.2014.05.018|issn=0896-6273}}</ref> Since her tool enabled long term labelling of memory associated neurons, she is able to observe memory traces overtime and reported that memory traces become more faint over time even though learned behaviors persist.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.columbiamedicinemagazine.org/features/spring-2014/optogenetics-revolution|title=The Optogenetics Revolution|last=cmm_admin|date=2014-06-01|website=Columbia Medicine Magazine|language=en|access-date=2020-04-05}}</ref> Her findings highlights the possibility that these memory traces are being redistributed to areas other than the hippocampus for even longer term storage.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.columbiamedicinemagazine.org/features/spring-2014/optogenetics-revolution|title=The Optogenetics Revolution|last=cmm_admin|date=2014-06-01|website=Columbia Medicine Magazine|language=en|access-date=2020-04-05}}</ref> She further used [[optogenetics]] to silence the cells involved the memory trace of contextual fear learning and showed that silencing inhibited expression of learned fear memories.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Denny|first=Christine\u00a0A.|last2=Kheirbek|first2=Mazen\u00a0A.|last3=Alba|first3=Eva\u00a0L.|last4=Tanaka|first4=Kenji\u00a0F.|last5=Brachman|first5=Rebecca\u00a0A.|last6=Laughman|first6=Kimberly\u00a0B.|last7=Tomm|first7=Nicole\u00a0K.|last8=Turi|first8=Gergely\u00a0F.|last9=Losonczy|first9=Attila|last10=Hen|first10=Ren\u00e9|date=2014-07-02|title=Hippocampal Memory Traces Are Differentially Modulated by Experience, Time, and Adult Neurogenesis|url=http://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/S0896627314004048|journal=Neuron|language=en|volume=83|issue=1|pages=189\u2013201|doi=10.1016/j.neuron.2014.05.018|issn=0896-6273}}</ref> Her work led to a first author paper in Neuron in 2014. Denny completed her PhD in 2012, and remained at Columbia to conduct postdoctoral work until 2013 in the Hen Laboratory.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.lyndhurstschools.net/1/Content2/20806|title=Lyndhurst High School|website=www.lyndhurstschools.net|access-date=2020-04-05}}</ref>\n\n== Career and Research ==\nAfter receiving an NIH DP5 Early Independence Award<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://conference.neuromodulation.org/item/794-christine-ann-denny-phd-associate-professor-of-clinical-neurobiology-in-psychiatry|title=Christine Ann Denny, PhD -- Honored Guest Lecturer|website=conference.neuromodulation.org|language=en-gb|access-date=2020-04-05}}</ref>, Denny started her own lab at Columbia University in 2013 and began her position as an Assistant Professor of Clinical Neurobiology in Psychiatry.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://portlandpress.com/neuronalsignal/pages/Editorial_board|title=Editorial Board|website=portlandpress.com|access-date=2020-04-05}}</ref> Denny also holds the title of Research Scientist V in the Division of\u00a0 Systems Neuroscience at the New York State Psychiatric Institute.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://portlandpress.com/neuronalsignal/pages/Editorial_board|title=Editorial Board|website=portlandpress.com|access-date=2020-04-05}}</ref> The research focus of the Denny Lab is understanding the neural basis of learning and memory and how these processes are altered in disease states such as [[Alzheimer's disease|Alzheimer\u2019s disease]] and depression.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://conference.neuromodulation.org/item/794-christine-ann-denny-phd-associate-professor-of-clinical-neurobiology-in-psychiatry|title=Christine Ann Denny, PhD -- Honored Guest Lecturer|website=conference.neuromodulation.org|language=en-gb|access-date=2020-04-05}}</ref> Denny\u2019s Lab uses the transgenic mice she helped develop in graduate school, ArcCreERT2 mice, to label memory traces and investigate what happens to them in disease models.\u00a0In 2015, Denny and her colleagues optimized their technique by using a more specific and time limited selective estrogen receptor modulator called 4-hydroxy tamoxifen instead of regular tamoxifen.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Cazzulino|first=Alejandro S.|last2=Martinez|first2=Randy|last3=Tomm|first3=Nicole K.|last4=Denny|first4=Christine A.|date=2016|title=Improved specificity of hippocampal memory trace labeling|url=https://onlinelibrary.wiley.com/doi/abs/10.1002/hipo.22556|journal=Hippocampus|language=en|volume=26|issue=6|pages=752\u2013762|doi=10.1002/hipo.22556|issn=1098-1063|pmc=PMC4867142|pmid=26662713}}</ref> This technique refined the ability to selectively label memory traces.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Cazzulino|first=Alejandro S.|last2=Martinez|first2=Randy|last3=Tomm|first3=Nicole K.|last4=Denny|first4=Christine A.|date=2016|title=Improved specificity of hippocampal memory trace labeling|url=https://onlinelibrary.wiley.com/doi/abs/10.1002/hipo.22556|journal=Hippocampus|language=en|volume=26|issue=6|pages=752\u2013762|doi=10.1002/hipo.22556|issn=1098-1063|pmc=PMC4867142|pmid=26662713}}</ref> Using this technique, Denny labelled neurons involved in novel social interaction and found that reactivation of these neurons during expression of learned fear responses decreases freezing.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Donaldson|first=Zoe|last2=Hen|first2=Ren\u00e9|last3=Gutzeit|first3=Vanessa|last4=Santos|first4=Tabia L.|last5=Sadsad|first5=Meghin|last6=Denny|first6=Christine A.|date=2016-10-01|title=25.2 SOCIAL BUFFERING OF CONDITIONED AND INNATE FEAR RESPONSES|url=https://www.jaacap.org/article/S0890-8567(16)30611-6/abstract|journal=Journal of the American Academy of Child & Adolescent Psychiatry|language=English|volume=55|issue=10|pages=S297|doi=10.1016/j.jaac.2016.07.262|issn=0890-8567}}</ref> These findings suggested the possibility of social neural circuits within the infralimbic prefrontal cortex as a therapeutic target for ameliorating anxiety or other disorders of learned fear associations.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Donaldson|first=Zoe|last2=Hen|first2=Ren\u00e9|last3=Gutzeit|first3=Vanessa|last4=Santos|first4=Tabia L.|last5=Sadsad|first5=Meghin|last6=Denny|first6=Christine A.|date=2016-10-01|title=25.2 SOCIAL BUFFERING OF CONDITIONED AND INNATE FEAR RESPONSES|url=https://www.jaacap.org/article/S0890-8567(16)30611-6/abstract|journal=Journal of the American Academy of Child & Adolescent Psychiatry|language=English|volume=55|issue=10|pages=S297|doi=10.1016/j.jaac.2016.07.262|issn=0890-8567}}</ref> In 2017, Denny then crossed her ArcCreERT2 mouse line with an Alzheimer\u2019s model mouse line (APP/PS1) to look at memory traces in a neurodegenerative disease model. When they specifically reactivated neuronal ensembles in the dentate gyrus implicated in contextual fear conditioning in APP/PS1 mice, they found a significant increase in memory retrieval compared to controls suggesting that activated previously learned memory traces in the dentate gyrus might rescue memory loss phenotypes in disease.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Perusini|first=Jennifer N.|last2=Cajigas|first2=Stephanie A.|last3=Cohensedgh|first3=Omid|last4=Lim|first4=Sean C.|last5=Pavlova|first5=Ina P.|last6=Donaldson|first6=Zoe R.|last7=Denny|first7=Christine A.|date=2017|title=Optogenetic stimulation of dentate gyrus engrams restores memory in Alzheimer's disease mice|url=https://onlinelibrary.wiley.com/doi/abs/10.1002/hipo.22756|journal=Hippocampus|language=en|volume=27|issue=10|pages=1110\u20131122|doi=10.1002/hipo.22756|issn=1098-1063|pmc=PMC5610644|pmid=28667669}}</ref>\n\nDenny\u2019s lab also investigates small molecule prophylactics for stress-induced depressive-like behavior.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://cadennylab.com/|title=The Denny Laboratory|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-05}}</ref> Since psychiatric illnesses often follow stressful events, Denny has proposed the importance of prophylactic therapies in preventing susceptible individuals from developing psychiatric disorders after stressful events. One of the molecules Denny has been exploring the prophylactic therapeutic benefit of is ketamine, a fast acting antidepressant.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://cadennylab.com/|title=The Denny Laboratory|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-05}}</ref> In 2015, Denny found that when ketamine is administered one week prior to various stress paradigms in mice, the effects of the stress paradigm are ameliorated and they do not show as robust depressive phenotypes.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Brachman|first=Rebecca A.|last2=McGowan|first2=Josephine C.|last3=Perusini|first3=Jennifer N.|last4=Lim|first4=Sean C.|last5=Pham|first5=Thu Ha|last6=Faye|first6=Charlene|last7=Gardier|first7=Alain M.|last8=Mendez-David|first8=Indira|last9=David|first9=Denis J.|last10=Hen|first10=Ren\u00e9|last11=Denny|first11=Christine A.|date=2016-05-01|title=Ketamine as a Prophylactic Against Stress-Induced Depressive-like Behavior|url=https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/26037911|journal=Biological Psychiatry|volume=79|issue=9|pages=776\u2013786|doi=10.1016/j.biopsych.2015.04.022|issn=1873-2402|pmc=4633406|pmid=26037911}}</ref> In a follow-up paper in 2017, Denny and her lab found that administering ketamine right before or right after a fearful event did not protect against fearful events, while administration one week before a stressful event still seemed to provide prophylactic effects and decrease fear responses.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=McGowan|first=Josephine C|last2=LaGamma|first2=Christina T|last3=Lim|first3=Sean C|last4=Tsitsiklis|first4=Melina|last5=Neria|first5=Yuval|last6=Brachman|first6=Rebecca A|last7=Denny|first7=Christine A|date=2017-07|title=Prophylactic Ketamine Attenuates Learned Fear|url=https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC5518899/|journal=Neuropsychopharmacology|volume=42|issue=8|pages=1577\u20131589|doi=10.1038/npp.2017.19|issn=0893-133X|pmc=5518899|pmid=28128336}}</ref> After these findings, Denny was interested in looking at the markers of stress resilience following ketamine treatment.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=McGowan|first=Josephine C.|last2=Hill|first2=Collin|last3=Mastrodonato|first3=Alessia|last4=LaGamma|first4=Christina T.|last5=Kitayev|first5=Alexander|last6=Brachman|first6=Rebecca A.|last7=Narain|first7=Niven R.|last8=Kiebish|first8=Michael A.|last9=Denny|first9=Christine A.|date=2018-08|title=Prophylactic ketamine alters nucleotide and neurotransmitter metabolism in brain and plasma following stress|url=https://www.nature.com/articles/s41386-018-0043-7|journal=Neuropsychopharmacology|language=en|volume=43|issue=9|pages=1813\u20131821|doi=10.1038/s41386-018-0043-7|issn=1740-634X}}</ref> In a Nature paper in 2018, Denny found 8 metabolites that were changed in the prefrontal cortex and hippocampus after ketamine administration. One novel finding was that precursors to inhibitory neurotransmitters were increased whereas those for excitatory neurotransmitters were decreased.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=McGowan|first=Josephine C.|last2=Hill|first2=Collin|last3=Mastrodonato|first3=Alessia|last4=LaGamma|first4=Christina T.|last5=Kitayev|first5=Alexander|last6=Brachman|first6=Rebecca A.|last7=Narain|first7=Niven R.|last8=Kiebish|first8=Michael A.|last9=Denny|first9=Christine A.|date=2018-08|title=Prophylactic ketamine alters nucleotide and neurotransmitter metabolism in brain and plasma following stress|url=https://www.nature.com/articles/s41386-018-0043-7|journal=Neuropsychopharmacology|language=en|volume=43|issue=9|pages=1813\u20131821|doi=10.1038/s41386-018-0043-7|issn=1740-634X}}</ref> This was one of the first findings showing a substrate for the prophylactic effects of ketamine on stress-induced depression.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=McGowan|first=Josephine C.|last2=Hill|first2=Collin|last3=Mastrodonato|first3=Alessia|last4=LaGamma|first4=Christina T.|last5=Kitayev|first5=Alexander|last6=Brachman|first6=Rebecca A.|last7=Narain|first7=Niven R.|last8=Kiebish|first8=Michael A.|last9=Denny|first9=Christine A.|date=2018-08|title=Prophylactic ketamine alters nucleotide and neurotransmitter metabolism in brain and plasma following stress|url=https://www.nature.com/articles/s41386-018-0043-7|journal=Neuropsychopharmacology|language=en|volume=43|issue=9|pages=1813\u20131821|doi=10.1038/s41386-018-0043-7|issn=1740-634X}}</ref> Denny then looked at another prophylactic in comparison to ketamine, prucalopride - a 5-HT4Rgonist, and found that both have the ability to decrease stress-induced depressive-like behaviors and both alter AMPAR mediated synaptic transmission in the CA3 of the hippocampus.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Chen|first=Briana K.|last2=Mendez-David|first2=Indira|last3=Luna|first3=Victor M.|last4=Faye|first4=Charl\u00e8ne|last5=Gardier|first5=Alain M.|last6=David|first6=Denis J.|last7=Denny|first7=Christine A.|date=2020-02|title=Prophylactic efficacy of 5-HT 4 R agonists against stress|url=https://www.nature.com/articles/s41386-019-0540-3|journal=Neuropsychopharmacology|language=en|volume=45|issue=3|pages=542\u2013552|doi=10.1038/s41386-019-0540-3|issn=1740-634X}}</ref>\n\n== Awards and Honors ==\n\n* NIH Early Independence Award<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://womeninscienceatcolumbia.org/symposium/speakers/|title=Speakers|date=2018-04-03|website=Women in Science at Columbia|language=en|access-date=2020-04-05}}</ref>\n* ELabNYC Fellow<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://womeninscienceatcolumbia.org/symposium/speakers/|title=Speakers|date=2018-04-03|website=Women in Science at Columbia|language=en|access-date=2020-04-05}}</ref>\n* 2017 Inductee into the Lyndhurst High School Academic Hall Of Fame<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.lyndhurstschools.net/1/Content2/20806|title=Lyndhurst High School|website=www.lyndhurstschools.net|access-date=2020-04-05}}</ref>\n* Brain & Behavior Research Foundation (BBRF), NARSAD Young Investigator Award, 2015-2017<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.lyndhurstschools.net/1/Content2/20806|title=Lyndhurst High School|website=www.lyndhurstschools.net|access-date=2020-04-05}}</ref>\n* American Society for Neurochemistry Travel Award<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.lyndhurstschools.net/1/Content2/20806|title=Lyndhurst High School|website=www.lyndhurstschools.net|access-date=2020-04-05}}</ref>\n* Molecular and Cellular Cognition Society Young Travel Fellowship<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://commonfund.nih.gov/earlyindependence/awardrecipients13|title=NIH Director's Early Independence Award Program - 2013 Award Recipients {{!}} NIH Common Fund|website=commonfund.nih.gov|access-date=2020-04-05}}</ref>\n\n== Publications ==\n\n* Cazzulino AS, Martinez R, Tomm NK, and Denny CA. (2015) Improved specificity of hippocampal memory trace labeling. Hippocampus. (in press)<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://cadennylab.com/842-2/|title=Publications {{!}} The Denny Laboratory|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-05}}</ref>\n* Brachman RA, McGowan JC, Perusini JN, Lim SC, Pham TH, Faye C, Gardier AM, Mendez-David I, David DJ, Hen R, and Denny CA. (2015) Ketamine as a prophylactic against stress-induced depressive-like behavior. Biological Psychiatry. (in press).<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://cadennylab.com/842-2/|title=Publications {{!}} The Denny Laboratory|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-05}}</ref>\n* Root CM, Denny CA, Hen R, and Axel R. (2014) The participation of cortical amygdala in innate, odour-driven behaviour. Nature 515:269-273. PMID: 25383519.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Root|first=Cory M.|last2=Denny|first2=Christine A.|last3=Hen|first3=Ren\u00e9|last4=Axel|first4=Richard|date=2014-11-13|title=The participation of cortical amygdala in innate, odour-driven behaviour|url=https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/25383519|journal=Nature|volume=515|issue=7526|pages=269\u2013273|doi=10.1038/nature13897|issn=1476-4687|pmc=4231015|pmid=25383519}}</ref>\n* Denny CA, Kheirbek MA, Alba EL, Tanaka KF, Brachman RA, Laughman KB, Tomm NK, Turi GF, Losonczy A, and\n* Hen R. (2014) Hippocampal memory traces are differentially modulated by experience, time, and adult neurogenesis. Neuron 83:189-201. PMID: 24991962.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Denny|first=Christine A.|last2=Kheirbek|first2=Mazen A.|last3=Alba|first3=Eva L.|last4=Tanaka|first4=Kenji F.|last5=Brachman|first5=Rebecca A.|last6=Laughman|first6=Kimberly B.|last7=Tomm|first7=Nicole K.|last8=Turi|first8=Gergely F.|last9=Losonczy|first9=Attila|last10=Hen|first10=Ren\u00e9|date=2014-07-02|title=Hippocampal memory traces are differentially modulated by experience, time, and adult neurogenesis|url=https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/24991962|journal=Neuron|volume=83|issue=1|pages=189\u2013201|doi=10.1016/j.neuron.2014.05.018|issn=1097-4199|pmc=4169172|pmid=24991962}}</ref>\n* Oury F, Khrimian L, Denny CA, Gardin A, Chamouni A, Goeden N, Huang Y, Srinivas P, Gao X-B, Suyama S, Thomas L, Mann JJ, Horvath T, Bonnin A, and Karsenty G. (2013) Maternal and offspring pools of osteocalcin influence brain development and functions. Cell. 26:228-241. PMID: 24074871.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Oury|first=Franck|last2=Khrimian|first2=Lori|last3=Denny|first3=Christine\u00a0A.|last4=Gardin|first4=Antoine|last5=Chamouni|first5=Alexandre|last6=Goeden|first6=Nick|last7=Huang|first7=Yung-yu|last8=Lee|first8=Hojoon|last9=Srinivas|first9=Prashanth|last10=Gao|first10=Xiao-Bing|last11=Suyama|first11=Shigetomo|date=2013-09-26|title=Maternal and Offspring Pools of Osteocalcin Influence Brain Development and Functions|url=http://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/S0092867413010738|journal=Cell|language=en|volume=155|issue=1|pages=228\u2013241|doi=10.1016/j.cell.2013.08.042|issn=0092-8674}}</ref>\n* Denny CA, Burghardt NS, Schacter DM, Hen R, and Drew MR. (2012) 4- to 6-week-old adult-born hippocampal neurons influence novelty-evoked exploration and contextual fear conditioning. Hippocampus. 22:1188-1201. PMID: 21739523.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Denny|first=Christine A.|last2=Burghardt|first2=Nesha S.|last3=Schachter|first3=Daniel M.|last4=Hen|first4=Ren\u00e9|last5=Drew|first5=Michael R.|date=2012-05|title=4- to 6-week-old adult-born hippocampal neurons influence novelty-evoked exploration and contextual fear conditioning|url=https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/21739523|journal=Hippocampus|volume=22|issue=5|pages=1188\u20131201|doi=10.1002/hipo.20964|issn=1098-1063|pmc=3193906|pmid=21739523}}</ref>\n* Drew MR, Denny CA, and Hen R. (2010) Arrest of adult hippocampal neurogenesis impairs single- but not multiple-trial contextual fear conditioning. Behav Neurosci. 124:446-454. PMID: 20695644.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Drew|first=Michael R.|last2=Denny|first2=Christine A.|last3=Hen|first3=Rene|date=2010-08|title=Arrest of adult hippocampal neurogenesis in mice impairs single- but not multiple-trial contextual fear conditioning|url=https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/20695644|journal=Behavioral Neuroscience|volume=124|issue=4|pages=446\u2013454|doi=10.1037/a0020081|issn=1939-0084|pmc=2925248|pmid=20695644}}</ref>\n* Pollak DD, Monje FJ, Zuckerman L, Denny CA, Drew MR, and Kandel ER. (2008) An animal model of a behavioral intervention for depression. Neuron 60, 149-161. PMID: 18940595.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Pollak|first=Daniela D.|last2=Monje|first2=Francisco J.|last3=Zuckerman|first3=Lee|last4=Denny|first4=Christine A.|last5=Drew|first5=Michael R.|last6=Kandel|first6=Eric R.|date=2008-10-09|title=AN ANIMAL MODEL OF A BEHAVIORAL INTERVENTION FOR DEPRESSION|url=https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC3417703/|journal=Neuron|volume=60|issue=1|pages=149\u2013161|doi=10.1016/j.neuron.2008.07.041|issn=0896-6273|pmc=3417703|pmid=18940595}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{{authority control}}\n\n{{no cats|date=April 2020}}\n", "text_old": "{{short description|American neuroscientist}}\n{{cleanup|reason=duplicate refs, [[WP:NAMEDREFS]] are needed.|date=April 2020}}\n'''Christine Denny''' is an American neuroscientist and Associate Professor of Clinical Neurobiology in Psychiatry in the Department of Psychiatry at [[Columbia University]] Irving Medical Center in New York City. Denny investigates the molecular mechanisms underlying learning and memory is well known for her development of a novel technique to label neurons that encode specific memories. She uses this technique to probe what happens to [[Hippocampus|hippocampal]] memory traces in different disease states. {{Infobox scientist\n| name              = Christine Ann Denny\n| image             = \n| image_size        = \n| caption           = \n| birth_date        = \n| birth_place       = \n| nationality       = American\n| fields            = Neuroscience\n| workplaces        = Columbia University\n| alma_mater        = Boston College\n| known_for         = ArcCreERT2 transgenic mouse line for memory tracing\n| awards            = NIH Early Independence Award, ELabNYC Fellow, Inductee into the Lyndhurst High School Academic Hall Of Fame, Brain & Behavior Research Foundation NARSAD Young Investigator Award, American Society for Neurochemistry Travel Award, Molecular and Cellular Cognition Society Young Travel Fellowship\n| Institutions      = Columbia University\n}}\n\n== Early Life and Education ==\nDenny grew up in New Jersey and attended Lyndhurst High School.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.lyndhurstschools.net/1/Content2/20806|title=Lyndhurst High School|website=www.lyndhurstschools.net|access-date=2020-04-05}}</ref>\u00a0Denny excelled in her academic pursuits in high school and received multiple scholarships, was recognized for her leadership at the state level, and graduated as class [[Salutatorian]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.lyndhurstschools.net/1/Content2/20806|title=Lyndhurst High School|website=www.lyndhurstschools.net|access-date=2020-04-05}}</ref> Denny was also actively involved in athletics and received varsity letters in volleyball and track and field.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.lyndhurstschools.net/1/Content2/20806|title=Lyndhurst High School|website=www.lyndhurstschools.net|access-date=2020-04-05}}</ref>\n\nAfter graduating from Lyndhurst in 2001, Denny then pursued her undergraduate studies at [[Boston College]] where she received a Bachelors of Science majoring in Biological Sciences and minoring in Theology.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.lyndhurstschools.net/1/Content2/20806|title=Lyndhurst High School|website=www.lyndhurstschools.net|access-date=2020-04-05}}</ref> While at Boston College, Denny continued to excel in academics as she maintained Honor and Dean\u2019s List standing but she also became interested in research and received an Advanced Undergraduate Research Fellowship to support her research. In 2004, Denny began roles as a teaching assistant and laboratory instructor at Boston College.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.lyndhurstschools.net/1/Content2/20806|title=Lyndhurst High School|website=www.lyndhurstschools.net|access-date=2020-04-05}}</ref> After she graduated in 2005, Denny continued in academia pursuing a Masters in Biology at Boston College.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://portlandpress.com/neuronalsignal/pages/Editorial_board|title=Editorial Board|website=portlandpress.com|access-date=2020-04-05}}</ref> While at Boston College, Denny worked under the mentorship of Dr. [[Thomas N. Seyfried]] studying lipid storage diseases and metabolic therapies to treat brain diseases.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bc.edu/bc-web/schools/mcas/departments/biology/people/faculty-directory/thomas-seyfried.html|title=Thomas N. Seyfried - Biology - Morrissey College of Arts and Sciences - Boston College|website=www.bc.edu|language=en|access-date=2020-04-05}}</ref> In 2007, Denny published a first author paper in the Journal of Neurochemistry highlighting a model system for assessing retinal pathobiology and therapies for [[ganglioside]] storage diseases.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Denny|first=Christine A.|last2=Alroy|first2=Joseph|last3=Pawlyk|first3=Basil S.|last4=Sandberg|first4=Michael A.|last5=D\u2019Azzo|first5=Alessandra|last6=Seyfried|first6=Thomas N.|date=2007|title=Neurochemical, morphological, and neurophysiological abnormalities in retinas of Sandhoff and GM1 gangliosidosis mice|url=https://onlinelibrary.wiley.com/doi/abs/10.1111/j.1471-4159.2007.04525.x|journal=Journal of Neurochemistry|language=en|volume=101|issue=5|pages=1294\u20131302|doi=10.1111/j.1471-4159.2007.04525.x|issn=1471-4159}}</ref> Denny also explored lipid abnormalities in mouse models of [[Rett syndrome|Rett Syndrome]]<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Seyfried|first=Thomas N.|last2=Heinecke|first2=Karie A.|last3=Mantis|first3=John G.|last4=Denny|first4=Christine A.|date=2008-11-11|title=Brain Lipid Analysis in Mice with Rett Syndrome|url=https://doi.org/10.1007/s11064-008-9874-7|journal=Neurochemical Research|language=en|volume=34|issue=6|pages=1057|doi=10.1007/s11064-008-9874-7|issn=1573-6903|pmc=PMC4286142|pmid=19002580}}</ref> as well as the effects of\u00a0 ketogenic diets on alleviating symptoms of [[Sandhoff disease]], a ganglioside storage disease.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Denny|first=Christine A.|last2=Heinecke|first2=Karie A.|last3=Kim|first3=Youngho P.|last4=Baek|first4=Rena C.|last5=Loh|first5=Katrina S.|last6=Butters|first6=Terry D.|last7=Bronson|first7=Roderick T.|last8=Platt|first8=Frances M.|last9=Seyfried|first9=Thomas N.|date=2010|title=Restricted ketogenic diet enhances the therapeutic action of N-butyldeoxynojirimycin towards brain GM2 accumulation in adult Sandhoff disease mice|url=https://onlinelibrary.wiley.com/doi/abs/10.1111/j.1471-4159.2010.06733.x|journal=Journal of Neurochemistry|language=en|volume=113|issue=6|pages=1525\u20131535|doi=10.1111/j.1471-4159.2010.06733.x|issn=1471-4159}}</ref>\n\nDenny then pursued a PhD in neuroscience at [[Columbia University]] under the mentorship of Dr. Rene Hen.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.columbiamedicinemagazine.org/features/spring-2014/optogenetics-revolution|title=The Optogenetics Revolution|last=cmm_admin|date=2014-06-01|website=Columbia Medicine Magazine|language=en|access-date=2020-04-05}}</ref> Denny first explored hippocampal neurogenesis and published a first author paper in 2010 showing that inhibiting neurogenesis increases novel object exploration and impairs one trial contextual fear-learning in mice suggesting an important role for adult born neurons in cognitive function.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Denny|first=Christine A.|last2=Burghardt|first2=Nesha S.|last3=Schachter|first3=Daniel M.|last4=Hen|first4=Ren\u00e9|last5=Drew|first5=Michael R.|date=2012|title=4- to 6-week-old adult-born hippocampal neurons influence novelty-evoked exploration and contextual fear conditioning|url=https://onlinelibrary.wiley.com/doi/abs/10.1002/hipo.20964|journal=Hippocampus|language=en|volume=22|issue=5|pages=1188\u20131201|doi=10.1002/hipo.20964|issn=1098-1063|pmc=PMC3193906|pmid=21739523}}</ref> Denny then began to exploring the idea of memory traces, cells in the brain where memories are stored, and tried to tag these memory traces in the dentate gyrus and C3 regions of the hippocampus.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Denny|first=Christine\u00a0A.|last2=Kheirbek|first2=Mazen\u00a0A.|last3=Alba|first3=Eva\u00a0L.|last4=Tanaka|first4=Kenji\u00a0F.|last5=Brachman|first5=Rebecca\u00a0A.|last6=Laughman|first6=Kimberly\u00a0B.|last7=Tomm|first7=Nicole\u00a0K.|last8=Turi|first8=Gergely\u00a0F.|last9=Losonczy|first9=Attila|last10=Hen|first10=Ren\u00e9|date=2014-07-02|title=Hippocampal Memory Traces Are Differentially Modulated by Experience, Time, and Adult Neurogenesis|url=http://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/S0896627314004048|journal=Neuron|language=en|volume=83|issue=1|pages=189\u2013201|doi=10.1016/j.neuron.2014.05.018|issn=0896-6273}}</ref> She was able to develop a genetic tool that enabled her to fluorescently tag neurons that were activated in specific memories.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Denny|first=Christine\u00a0A.|last2=Kheirbek|first2=Mazen\u00a0A.|last3=Alba|first3=Eva\u00a0L.|last4=Tanaka|first4=Kenji\u00a0F.|last5=Brachman|first5=Rebecca\u00a0A.|last6=Laughman|first6=Kimberly\u00a0B.|last7=Tomm|first7=Nicole\u00a0K.|last8=Turi|first8=Gergely\u00a0F.|last9=Losonczy|first9=Attila|last10=Hen|first10=Ren\u00e9|date=2014-07-02|title=Hippocampal Memory Traces Are Differentially Modulated by Experience, Time, and Adult Neurogenesis|url=http://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/S0896627314004048|journal=Neuron|language=en|volume=83|issue=1|pages=189\u2013201|doi=10.1016/j.neuron.2014.05.018|issn=0896-6273}}</ref> Since her tool enabled long term labelling of memory associated neurons, she is able to observe memory traces overtime and reported that memory traces become more faint over time even though learned behaviors persist.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.columbiamedicinemagazine.org/features/spring-2014/optogenetics-revolution|title=The Optogenetics Revolution|last=cmm_admin|date=2014-06-01|website=Columbia Medicine Magazine|language=en|access-date=2020-04-05}}</ref> Her findings highlights the possibility that these memory traces are being redistributed to areas other than the hippocampus for even longer term storage.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.columbiamedicinemagazine.org/features/spring-2014/optogenetics-revolution|title=The Optogenetics Revolution|last=cmm_admin|date=2014-06-01|website=Columbia Medicine Magazine|language=en|access-date=2020-04-05}}</ref> She further used [[optogenetics]] to silence the cells involved the memory trace of contextual fear learning and showed that silencing inhibited expression of learned fear memories.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Denny|first=Christine\u00a0A.|last2=Kheirbek|first2=Mazen\u00a0A.|last3=Alba|first3=Eva\u00a0L.|last4=Tanaka|first4=Kenji\u00a0F.|last5=Brachman|first5=Rebecca\u00a0A.|last6=Laughman|first6=Kimberly\u00a0B.|last7=Tomm|first7=Nicole\u00a0K.|last8=Turi|first8=Gergely\u00a0F.|last9=Losonczy|first9=Attila|last10=Hen|first10=Ren\u00e9|date=2014-07-02|title=Hippocampal Memory Traces Are Differentially Modulated by Experience, Time, and Adult Neurogenesis|url=http://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/S0896627314004048|journal=Neuron|language=en|volume=83|issue=1|pages=189\u2013201|doi=10.1016/j.neuron.2014.05.018|issn=0896-6273}}</ref> Her work led to a first author paper in Neuron in 2014. Denny completed her PhD in 2012, and remained at Columbia to conduct postdoctoral work until 2013 in the Hen Laboratory.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.lyndhurstschools.net/1/Content2/20806|title=Lyndhurst High School|website=www.lyndhurstschools.net|access-date=2020-04-05}}</ref> \n\n== Career and Research ==\nAfter receiving an NIH DP5 Early Independence Award<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://conference.neuromodulation.org/item/794-christine-ann-denny-phd-associate-professor-of-clinical-neurobiology-in-psychiatry|title=Christine Ann Denny, PhD -- Honored Guest Lecturer|website=conference.neuromodulation.org|language=en-gb|access-date=2020-04-05}}</ref>, Denny started her own lab at Columbia University in 2013 and began her position as an Assistant Professor of Clinical Neurobiology in Psychiatry.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://portlandpress.com/neuronalsignal/pages/Editorial_board|title=Editorial Board|website=portlandpress.com|access-date=2020-04-05}}</ref> Denny also holds the title of Research Scientist V in the Division of\u00a0 Systems Neuroscience at the New York State Psychiatric Institute.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://portlandpress.com/neuronalsignal/pages/Editorial_board|title=Editorial Board|website=portlandpress.com|access-date=2020-04-05}}</ref> The research focus of the Denny Lab is understanding the neural basis of learning and memory and how these processes are altered in disease states such as [[Alzheimer's disease|Alzheimer\u2019s disease]] and depression.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://conference.neuromodulation.org/item/794-christine-ann-denny-phd-associate-professor-of-clinical-neurobiology-in-psychiatry|title=Christine Ann Denny, PhD -- Honored Guest Lecturer|website=conference.neuromodulation.org|language=en-gb|access-date=2020-04-05}}</ref> Denny\u2019s Lab uses the transgenic mice she helped develop in graduate school, ArcCreERT2 mice, to label memory traces and investigate what happens to them in disease models.\u00a0In 2015, Denny and her colleagues optimized their technique by using a more specific and time limited selective estrogen receptor modulator called 4-hydroxy tamoxifen instead of regular tamoxifen.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Cazzulino|first=Alejandro S.|last2=Martinez|first2=Randy|last3=Tomm|first3=Nicole K.|last4=Denny|first4=Christine A.|date=2016|title=Improved specificity of hippocampal memory trace labeling|url=https://onlinelibrary.wiley.com/doi/abs/10.1002/hipo.22556|journal=Hippocampus|language=en|volume=26|issue=6|pages=752\u2013762|doi=10.1002/hipo.22556|issn=1098-1063|pmc=PMC4867142|pmid=26662713}}</ref> This technique refined the ability to selectively label memory traces.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Cazzulino|first=Alejandro S.|last2=Martinez|first2=Randy|last3=Tomm|first3=Nicole K.|last4=Denny|first4=Christine A.|date=2016|title=Improved specificity of hippocampal memory trace labeling|url=https://onlinelibrary.wiley.com/doi/abs/10.1002/hipo.22556|journal=Hippocampus|language=en|volume=26|issue=6|pages=752\u2013762|doi=10.1002/hipo.22556|issn=1098-1063|pmc=PMC4867142|pmid=26662713}}</ref> Using this technique, Denny labelled neurons involved in novel social interaction and found that reactivation of these neurons during expression of learned fear responses decreases freezing.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Donaldson|first=Zoe|last2=Hen|first2=Ren\u00e9|last3=Gutzeit|first3=Vanessa|last4=Santos|first4=Tabia L.|last5=Sadsad|first5=Meghin|last6=Denny|first6=Christine A.|date=2016-10-01|title=25.2 SOCIAL BUFFERING OF CONDITIONED AND INNATE FEAR RESPONSES|url=https://www.jaacap.org/article/S0890-8567(16)30611-6/abstract|journal=Journal of the American Academy of Child & Adolescent Psychiatry|language=English|volume=55|issue=10|pages=S297|doi=10.1016/j.jaac.2016.07.262|issn=0890-8567}}</ref> These findings suggested the possibility of social neural circuits within the infralimbic prefrontal cortex as a therapeutic target for ameliorating anxiety or other disorders of learned fear associations.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Donaldson|first=Zoe|last2=Hen|first2=Ren\u00e9|last3=Gutzeit|first3=Vanessa|last4=Santos|first4=Tabia L.|last5=Sadsad|first5=Meghin|last6=Denny|first6=Christine A.|date=2016-10-01|title=25.2 SOCIAL BUFFERING OF CONDITIONED AND INNATE FEAR RESPONSES|url=https://www.jaacap.org/article/S0890-8567(16)30611-6/abstract|journal=Journal of the American Academy of Child & Adolescent Psychiatry|language=English|volume=55|issue=10|pages=S297|doi=10.1016/j.jaac.2016.07.262|issn=0890-8567}}</ref> In 2017, Denny then crossed her ArcCreERT2 mouse line with an Alzheimer\u2019s model mouse line (APP/PS1) to look at memory traces in a neurodegenerative disease model. When they specifically reactivated neuronal ensembles in the dentate gyrus implicated in contextual fear conditioning in APP/PS1 mice, they found a significant increase in memory retrieval compared to controls suggesting that activated previously learned memory traces in the dentate gyrus might rescue memory loss phenotypes in disease.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Perusini|first=Jennifer N.|last2=Cajigas|first2=Stephanie A.|last3=Cohensedgh|first3=Omid|last4=Lim|first4=Sean C.|last5=Pavlova|first5=Ina P.|last6=Donaldson|first6=Zoe R.|last7=Denny|first7=Christine A.|date=2017|title=Optogenetic stimulation of dentate gyrus engrams restores memory in Alzheimer's disease mice|url=https://onlinelibrary.wiley.com/doi/abs/10.1002/hipo.22756|journal=Hippocampus|language=en|volume=27|issue=10|pages=1110\u20131122|doi=10.1002/hipo.22756|issn=1098-1063|pmc=PMC5610644|pmid=28667669}}</ref>\n\nDenny\u2019s lab also investigates small molecule prophylactics for stress-induced depressive-like behavior.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://cadennylab.com/|title=The Denny Laboratory|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-05}}</ref> Since psychiatric illnesses often follow stressful events, Denny has proposed the importance of prophylactic therapies in preventing susceptible individuals from developing psychiatric disorders after stressful events. One of the molecules Denny has been exploring the prophylactic therapeutic benefit of is ketamine, a fast acting antidepressant.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://cadennylab.com/|title=The Denny Laboratory|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-05}}</ref> In 2015, Denny found that when ketamine is administered one week prior to various stress paradigms in mice, the effects of the stress paradigm are ameliorated and they do not show as robust depressive phenotypes.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Brachman|first=Rebecca A.|last2=McGowan|first2=Josephine C.|last3=Perusini|first3=Jennifer N.|last4=Lim|first4=Sean C.|last5=Pham|first5=Thu Ha|last6=Faye|first6=Charlene|last7=Gardier|first7=Alain M.|last8=Mendez-David|first8=Indira|last9=David|first9=Denis J.|last10=Hen|first10=Ren\u00e9|last11=Denny|first11=Christine A.|date=2016-05-01|title=Ketamine as a Prophylactic Against Stress-Induced Depressive-like Behavior|url=https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/26037911|journal=Biological Psychiatry|volume=79|issue=9|pages=776\u2013786|doi=10.1016/j.biopsych.2015.04.022|issn=1873-2402|pmc=4633406|pmid=26037911}}</ref> In a follow-up paper in 2017, Denny and her lab found that administering ketamine right before or right after a fearful event did not protect against fearful events, while administration one week before a stressful event still seemed to provide prophylactic effects and decrease fear responses.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=McGowan|first=Josephine C|last2=LaGamma|first2=Christina T|last3=Lim|first3=Sean C|last4=Tsitsiklis|first4=Melina|last5=Neria|first5=Yuval|last6=Brachman|first6=Rebecca A|last7=Denny|first7=Christine A|date=2017-07|title=Prophylactic Ketamine Attenuates Learned Fear|url=https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC5518899/|journal=Neuropsychopharmacology|volume=42|issue=8|pages=1577\u20131589|doi=10.1038/npp.2017.19|issn=0893-133X|pmc=5518899|pmid=28128336}}</ref> After these findings, Denny was interested in looking at the markers of stress resilience following ketamine treatment.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=McGowan|first=Josephine C.|last2=Hill|first2=Collin|last3=Mastrodonato|first3=Alessia|last4=LaGamma|first4=Christina T.|last5=Kitayev|first5=Alexander|last6=Brachman|first6=Rebecca A.|last7=Narain|first7=Niven R.|last8=Kiebish|first8=Michael A.|last9=Denny|first9=Christine A.|date=2018-08|title=Prophylactic ketamine alters nucleotide and neurotransmitter metabolism in brain and plasma following stress|url=https://www.nature.com/articles/s41386-018-0043-7|journal=Neuropsychopharmacology|language=en|volume=43|issue=9|pages=1813\u20131821|doi=10.1038/s41386-018-0043-7|issn=1740-634X}}</ref> In a Nature paper in 2018, Denny found 8 metabolites that were changed in the prefrontal cortex and hippocampus after ketamine administration. One novel finding was that precursors to inhibitory neurotransmitters were increased whereas those for excitatory neurotransmitters were decreased.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=McGowan|first=Josephine C.|last2=Hill|first2=Collin|last3=Mastrodonato|first3=Alessia|last4=LaGamma|first4=Christina T.|last5=Kitayev|first5=Alexander|last6=Brachman|first6=Rebecca A.|last7=Narain|first7=Niven R.|last8=Kiebish|first8=Michael A.|last9=Denny|first9=Christine A.|date=2018-08|title=Prophylactic ketamine alters nucleotide and neurotransmitter metabolism in brain and plasma following stress|url=https://www.nature.com/articles/s41386-018-0043-7|journal=Neuropsychopharmacology|language=en|volume=43|issue=9|pages=1813\u20131821|doi=10.1038/s41386-018-0043-7|issn=1740-634X}}</ref> This was one of the first findings showing a substrate for the prophylactic effects of ketamine on stress-induced depression.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=McGowan|first=Josephine C.|last2=Hill|first2=Collin|last3=Mastrodonato|first3=Alessia|last4=LaGamma|first4=Christina T.|last5=Kitayev|first5=Alexander|last6=Brachman|first6=Rebecca A.|last7=Narain|first7=Niven R.|last8=Kiebish|first8=Michael A.|last9=Denny|first9=Christine A.|date=2018-08|title=Prophylactic ketamine alters nucleotide and neurotransmitter metabolism in brain and plasma following stress|url=https://www.nature.com/articles/s41386-018-0043-7|journal=Neuropsychopharmacology|language=en|volume=43|issue=9|pages=1813\u20131821|doi=10.1038/s41386-018-0043-7|issn=1740-634X}}</ref> Denny then looked at another prophylactic in comparison to ketamine, prucalopride - a 5-HT4Rgonist, and found that both have the ability to decrease stress-induced depressive-like behaviors and both alter AMPAR mediated synaptic transmission in the CA3 of the hippocampus.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Chen|first=Briana K.|last2=Mendez-David|first2=Indira|last3=Luna|first3=Victor M.|last4=Faye|first4=Charl\u00e8ne|last5=Gardier|first5=Alain M.|last6=David|first6=Denis J.|last7=Denny|first7=Christine A.|date=2020-02|title=Prophylactic efficacy of 5-HT 4 R agonists against stress|url=https://www.nature.com/articles/s41386-019-0540-3|journal=Neuropsychopharmacology|language=en|volume=45|issue=3|pages=542\u2013552|doi=10.1038/s41386-019-0540-3|issn=1740-634X}}</ref>\n\n== Awards and Honors ==\n\n* NIH Early Independence Award<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://womeninscienceatcolumbia.org/symposium/speakers/|title=Speakers|date=2018-04-03|website=Women in Science at Columbia|language=en|access-date=2020-04-05}}</ref>\n* ELabNYC Fellow<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://womeninscienceatcolumbia.org/symposium/speakers/|title=Speakers|date=2018-04-03|website=Women in Science at Columbia|language=en|access-date=2020-04-05}}</ref>\n* 2017 Inductee into the Lyndhurst High School Academic Hall Of Fame<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.lyndhurstschools.net/1/Content2/20806|title=Lyndhurst High School|website=www.lyndhurstschools.net|access-date=2020-04-05}}</ref>\n* Brain & Behavior Research Foundation (BBRF), NARSAD Young Investigator Award, 2015-2017<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.lyndhurstschools.net/1/Content2/20806|title=Lyndhurst High School|website=www.lyndhurstschools.net|access-date=2020-04-05}}</ref>\n* American Society for Neurochemistry Travel Award<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.lyndhurstschools.net/1/Content2/20806|title=Lyndhurst High School|website=www.lyndhurstschools.net|access-date=2020-04-05}}</ref>\n* Molecular and Cellular Cognition Society Young Travel Fellowship<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://commonfund.nih.gov/earlyindependence/awardrecipients13|title=NIH Director's Early Independence Award Program - 2013 Award Recipients {{!}} NIH Common Fund|website=commonfund.nih.gov|access-date=2020-04-05}}</ref>\n\n== Publications ==\n\n* Cazzulino AS, Martinez R, Tomm NK, and Denny CA. (2015) Improved specificity of hippocampal memory trace labeling. Hippocampus. (in press)<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://cadennylab.com/842-2/|title=Publications {{!}} The Denny Laboratory|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-05}}</ref>\n* Brachman RA, McGowan JC, Perusini JN, Lim SC, Pham TH, Faye C, Gardier AM, Mendez-David I, David DJ, Hen R, and Denny CA. (2015) Ketamine as a prophylactic against stress-induced depressive-like behavior. Biological Psychiatry. (in press).<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://cadennylab.com/842-2/|title=Publications {{!}} The Denny Laboratory|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-05}}</ref>\n* Root CM, Denny CA, Hen R, and Axel R. (2014) The participation of cortical amygdala in innate, odour-driven behaviour. Nature 515:269-273. PMID: 25383519.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Root|first=Cory M.|last2=Denny|first2=Christine A.|last3=Hen|first3=Ren\u00e9|last4=Axel|first4=Richard|date=2014-11-13|title=The participation of cortical amygdala in innate, odour-driven behaviour|url=https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/25383519|journal=Nature|volume=515|issue=7526|pages=269\u2013273|doi=10.1038/nature13897|issn=1476-4687|pmc=4231015|pmid=25383519}}</ref>\n* Denny CA, Kheirbek MA, Alba EL, Tanaka KF, Brachman RA, Laughman KB, Tomm NK, Turi GF, Losonczy A, and\n* Hen R. (2014) Hippocampal memory traces are differentially modulated by experience, time, and adult neurogenesis. Neuron 83:189-201. PMID: 24991962.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Denny|first=Christine A.|last2=Kheirbek|first2=Mazen A.|last3=Alba|first3=Eva L.|last4=Tanaka|first4=Kenji F.|last5=Brachman|first5=Rebecca A.|last6=Laughman|first6=Kimberly B.|last7=Tomm|first7=Nicole K.|last8=Turi|first8=Gergely F.|last9=Losonczy|first9=Attila|last10=Hen|first10=Ren\u00e9|date=2014-07-02|title=Hippocampal memory traces are differentially modulated by experience, time, and adult neurogenesis|url=https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/24991962|journal=Neuron|volume=83|issue=1|pages=189\u2013201|doi=10.1016/j.neuron.2014.05.018|issn=1097-4199|pmc=4169172|pmid=24991962}}</ref>\n* Oury F, Khrimian L, Denny CA, Gardin A, Chamouni A, Goeden N, Huang Y, Srinivas P, Gao X-B, Suyama S, Thomas L, Mann JJ, Horvath T, Bonnin A, and Karsenty G. (2013) Maternal and offspring pools of osteocalcin influence brain development and functions. Cell. 26:228-241. PMID: 24074871.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Oury|first=Franck|last2=Khrimian|first2=Lori|last3=Denny|first3=Christine\u00a0A.|last4=Gardin|first4=Antoine|last5=Chamouni|first5=Alexandre|last6=Goeden|first6=Nick|last7=Huang|first7=Yung-yu|last8=Lee|first8=Hojoon|last9=Srinivas|first9=Prashanth|last10=Gao|first10=Xiao-Bing|last11=Suyama|first11=Shigetomo|date=2013-09-26|title=Maternal and Offspring Pools of Osteocalcin Influence Brain Development and Functions|url=http://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/S0092867413010738|journal=Cell|language=en|volume=155|issue=1|pages=228\u2013241|doi=10.1016/j.cell.2013.08.042|issn=0092-8674}}</ref>\n* Denny CA, Burghardt NS, Schacter DM, Hen R, and Drew MR. (2012) 4- to 6-week-old adult-born hippocampal neurons influence novelty-evoked exploration and contextual fear conditioning. Hippocampus. 22:1188-1201. PMID: 21739523.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Denny|first=Christine A.|last2=Burghardt|first2=Nesha S.|last3=Schachter|first3=Daniel M.|last4=Hen|first4=Ren\u00e9|last5=Drew|first5=Michael R.|date=2012-05|title=4- to 6-week-old adult-born hippocampal neurons influence novelty-evoked exploration and contextual fear conditioning|url=https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/21739523|journal=Hippocampus|volume=22|issue=5|pages=1188\u20131201|doi=10.1002/hipo.20964|issn=1098-1063|pmc=3193906|pmid=21739523}}</ref>\n* Drew MR, Denny CA, and Hen R. (2010) Arrest of adult hippocampal neurogenesis impairs single- but not multiple-trial contextual fear conditioning. Behav Neurosci. 124:446-454. PMID: 20695644.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Drew|first=Michael R.|last2=Denny|first2=Christine A.|last3=Hen|first3=Rene|date=2010-08|title=Arrest of adult hippocampal neurogenesis in mice impairs single- but not multiple-trial contextual fear conditioning|url=https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/20695644|journal=Behavioral Neuroscience|volume=124|issue=4|pages=446\u2013454|doi=10.1037/a0020081|issn=1939-0084|pmc=2925248|pmid=20695644}}</ref>\n* Pollak DD, Monje FJ, Zuckerman L, Denny CA, Drew MR, and Kandel ER. (2008) An animal model of a behavioral intervention for depression. Neuron 60, 149-161. PMID: 18940595.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Pollak|first=Daniela D.|last2=Monje|first2=Francisco J.|last3=Zuckerman|first3=Lee|last4=Denny|first4=Christine A.|last5=Drew|first5=Michael R.|last6=Kandel|first6=Eric R.|date=2008-10-09|title=AN ANIMAL MODEL OF A BEHAVIORAL INTERVENTION FOR DEPRESSION|url=https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC3417703/|journal=Neuron|volume=60|issue=1|pages=149\u2013161|doi=10.1016/j.neuron.2008.07.041|issn=0896-6273|pmc=3417703|pmid=18940595}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{{authority control}}\n\n{{no cats|date=April 2020}}\n", "name_user": "Kj cheetham", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eEarly Life and Education:Removed academic title", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Christine_Ann_Denny"}
{"title_page": "Ramona (1910 film)", "text_new": "{{short description|1910 film}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{Infobox film\n| name           = Ramona\n| image          = \n| caption        = \n| director       = [[D. W. Griffith]]\n| producer       = D. W. Griffith\n| writer         = [[Helen Hunt Jackson]] (novel)<br>D. W. Griffith<br>[[Stanner E. V. Taylor]]\n| starring       = [[Mary Pickford]]<br>[[Henry B. Walthall]]\n| cinematography = [[G. W. Bitzer]]\n| editing        = \n| distributor    = [[Biograph Company]] \n| released       = {{film date|1910|5|23}}\n| runtime        = 17 minutes\n| country        = United States \n| language       = Silent with English intertitles\n}}\n[[File:Ramona (1910).webm|thumb|thumbtime=1|upright=1.5|''Ramona'']]\n'''''Ramona''''' is a 1910 American [[short film|short]] [[drama film]] directed by [[D. W. Griffith]], based on [[Helen Hunt Jackson]]'s 1884 novel ''[[Ramona]].'' Through a love story, the early [[Silent film|silent]] short explores racial injustice to Native Americans and stars [[Mary Pickford]] and [[Henry B. Walthall]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.tcm.com/mediaroom/video/239855/Ramona-Movie-Clip-Opening.html|title=Ramona (1910) -- (Movie Clip) Opening|website=Turner Classic Movies|access-date=October 4, 2016}}</ref> A copy of the print survives in the [[Library of Congress]] film archive.<ref name=\"silentera\">{{cite web |url=http://www.silentera.com/PSFL/data/R/Ramona1910.html |title=Progressive Silent Film List: Ramona |accessdate=June 2, 2008|work=Silent Era}}</ref> The film was remade in 1928 (dir. [[Edwin Carewe]]) with [[Dolores del R\u00edo]] and 1936 (dir. [[Henry King (director)|Henry King]]) with [[Loretta Young]].\n\n==Plot==\n''Ramona'' chronicles the romance between Ramona ([[Mary Pickford]]), a Spanish orphan from the prestigious Moreno family, and Alessandro ([[Henry B. Walthall]]), an Indian who appears on her family's ranch one day. Ramona's foster mother's son Felipe ([[Francis J. Grandon]]) proclaims his love for Ramona, but she rejects him because she has fallen for Alessandro. They fall deeply in love, yet their desire to wed is denied by Ramona's foster mother, who reacts by exiling Alessandro from her ranch. He returns to his village, only to find that it has been demolished by white men. Meanwhile, Ramona is informed that she also has \"Indian blood\", which leads her to abandon everything she has to be with Alessandro. They marry, and live among the wreckage of Alessandro's devastated village. They have a child together and live at peace until the white men come to force them from their home as they claim the land. Their baby perishes, which adds to Alessandro's mental deterioration. Alessandro is then killed by the white men. A devastated Ramona then returns with Felipe back to her family back on the ranch.<ref>{{Cite web|url = https://www.imdb.com/title/tt0001371/plotsummary?ref_=tt_ov_pl|title = Ramona (1910) Plot Summary|date = |accessdate = September 30, 2015|website = IMDB|last = Moving Picture World}}</ref>\n\n==Production==\nAdvertisements for the film emphasized that it was made \"by arrangement with Little, Brown, & Company,\" the publishers of Jackson's novel. The film was shot on location in Ventura County, California, \"at identical locations wherein Mrs. Jackson placed her characters.\"<ref>{{Cite book|url=http://archive.org/details/filmindexjanjun105film|title=The Film Index (Jan-Jun 1910)|last=Films Publishing Co.|date=1910|publisher=New York, Films Publishing Co.|others=Media History Digital Library}}</ref> \n\nWhen D.W. Griffith directed ''Ramona'', the [[Biograph Company|Biograph]] production company had fallen into hard times. Still based in New York to rival the now broken up [[Edison Studios|Edison Company]], Biograph needed a fresh face. Griffith joined the company in 1908 as a writer and actor. Soon, however, the head director of the company, [[Wallace McCutcheon Sr.|Wallace McCutcheon]], fell ill and his son had little success with taking over for him. This led Grifith to become the principal director for the company, and the only director for films made at Biograph between June 1908 and December 1909.<ref>https://www.moma.org/documents/moma_catalogue_3465_300062291.pdf</ref> During these few months, Griffith turned out an exceptional amount of films, with estimates of one 12 minute and one 16 long minute piece per week. The company actually began its venture out West to Hollywood thanks to Griffith's work on ''Ramona'' because he wanted to film on location in Ventura, California.\n\nLongtime friend and colleague of Griffith's [[Billy Bitzer]] worked as the cinematographer for the film. Bitzer was hired originally as an electrician for the Biograph company, but his love of cameras pushed him to become one of cinema's most inventive pioneers. He experimented with photography, especially lighting and close-up shots. The Griffith and Bitzer duo formed shortly after Griffith directed his first film, ''[[The Adventures of Dollie]]'' and continued after both men left the Biograph production company in 1913.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.cobbles.com/simpp_archive/dwgriffith.htm |title=D. W. Griffith\u2014Independent Profile |work=Cobblestone Entertainment |accessdate=October 12, 2019}}</ref> Bitzer's experimental nature is beautifully showcased in the film's sweeping landscape shots of the California mountains and distinct editing techniques like [[cross-cutting]].\n\n==Cast==\n[[File:Mary Pickford cph.3c17995u.jpg|thumb|Mary Pickford, the actress who plays Ramona.]]\n\n*[[Mary Pickford]] as Ramona\n*[[Henry B. Walthall]] as Alessandro\n*[[Francis J. Grandon]] as Felipe\n*[[Kate Bruce]] as The Mother\n*[[W. Chrystie Miller]] as The Priest\n*[[Dorothy Bernard]]\n*[[Gertrude Claire]] as Woman in west\n*[[Robert Harron]]\n*[[Dell Henderson]] as Man at burial\n*[[Mae Marsh]]\n*Frank Opperman as Ranch hand\n*[[Anthony O'Sullivan]] as Ranch hand\n*[[Jack Pickford]] as A boy\n*[[Mack Sennett]] as White exploiter\n\n[[File:Henry B Walthall - Sep 1917 EH.jpg|thumb|Henry B Walthall, the actor who plays Alessandro.]]\n\n==See also==\n* [[List of American films of 1910]]\n* [[D. W. Griffith filmography]]\n* [[Mary Pickford filmography]]\n* [[Ramona (1928 film)]]\n* [[Ramona (1936 film)]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{IMDb title|id=0001371|title=Ramona}}\n* [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=6dO2mBb-_z8 ''Ramona''] on [[YouTube]]\n* {{Internet Archive film|id=Ramona_953|title=Ramona (1910 film)}}\n\n{{D. W. Griffith}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Ramona}}\n[[Category:1910 films]]\n[[Category:1910s drama films]]\n[[Category:1910s short films]]\n[[Category:American films]]\n[[Category:American drama films]]\n[[Category:American silent short films]]\n[[Category:American black-and-white films]]\n[[Category:Films based on American novels]]\n[[Category:Films set in California]]\n[[Category:Films directed by D. W. Griffith]]\n[[Category:Films with screenplays by Stanner E.V. Taylor]]\n[[Category:Films with screenplays by D. W. Griffith]]\n[[Category:Films based on Ramona by Helen Hunt Jackson]]\n[[Category:Articles containing video clips]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|1910 film}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=August 2019}}\n{{Infobox film\n| name           = Ramona\n| image          = \n| caption        = \n| director       = [[D. W. Griffith]]\n| producer       = D. W. Griffith\n| writer         = [[Helen Hunt Jackson]] (novel)<br>D. W. Griffith<br>[[Stanner E. V. Taylor]]\n| starring       = [[Mary Pickford]]<br>[[Henry B. Walthall]]\n| cinematography = [[G. W. Bitzer]]\n| editing        = \n| distributor    = [[Biograph Company]] \n| released       = {{film date|1910|5|23}}\n| runtime        = 17 minutes\n| country        = United States \n| language       = Silent with English intertitles\n}}\n[[File:Ramona (1910).webm|thumb|thumbtime=1|upright=1.5|''Ramona'']]\n'''''Ramona''''' is a 1910 American [[short film|short]] [[drama film]] directed by [[D. W. Griffith]], based on [[Helen Hunt Jackson]]'s 1884 novel ''[[Ramona]].'' Through a love story, the early [[Silent film|silent]] short explores racial injustice to Native Americans and stars [[Mary Pickford]] and [[Henry B. Walthall]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.tcm.com/mediaroom/video/239855/Ramona-Movie-Clip-Opening.html|title=Ramona (1910) -- (Movie Clip) Opening|website=Turner Classic Movies|access-date=October 4, 2016}}</ref> A copy of the print survives in the [[Library of Congress]] film archive.<ref name=\"silentera\">{{cite web |url=http://www.silentera.com/PSFL/data/R/Ramona1910.html |title=Progressive Silent Film List: Ramona |accessdate=June 2, 2008|work=Silent Era}}</ref> The film was remade in 1928 (dir. [[Edwin Carewe]]) with [[Dolores del R\u00edo]] and 1936 (dir. [[Henry King (director)|Henry King]]) with [[Loretta Young]].\n\n==Plot==\n''Ramona'' chronicles the romance between Ramona ([[Mary Pickford]]), a Spanish orphan from the prestigious Moreno family, and Alessandro ([[Henry B. Walthall]]), an Indian who appears on her family's ranch one day. Ramona's foster mother's son Felipe ([[Francis J. Grandon]]) proclaims his love for Ramona, but she rejects him because she has fallen for Alessandro. They fall deeply in love, yet their desire to wed is denied by Ramona's foster mother, who reacts by exiling Alessandro from her ranch. He returns to his village, only to find that it has been demolished by white men. Meanwhile, Ramona is informed that she also has \"Indian blood\", which leads her to abandon everything she has to be with Alessandro. They marry, and live among the wreckage of Alessandro's devastated village. They have a child together and live at peace until the white men come to force them from their home as they claim the land. Their baby perishes, which adds to Alessandro's mental deterioration. Alessandro is then killed by the white men. A devastated Ramona then returns with Felipe back to her family back on the ranch.<ref>{{Cite web|url = https://www.imdb.com/title/tt0001371/plotsummary?ref_=tt_ov_pl|title = Ramona (1910) Plot Summary|date = |accessdate = September 30, 2015|website = IMDB|last = Moving Picture World}}</ref>\n\n==Production==\nAdvertisements for the film emphasized that it was made \"by arrangement with Little, Brown, & Company,\" the publishers of Jackson's novel. The film was shot on location in Ventura County, California, \"at identical locations wherein Mrs. Jackson placed her characters.\"<ref>{{Cite book|url=http://archive.org/details/filmindexjanjun105film|title=The Film Index (Jan-Jun 1910)|last=Films Publishing Co.|date=1910|publisher=New York, Films Publishing Co.|others=Media History Digital Library}}</ref> \n\nWhen D.W. Griffith directed ''Ramona'', the [[Biograph Company|Biograph]] production company had fallen into hard times. Still based in New York to rival the now broken up [[Edison Studios|Edison Company]], Biograph needed a fresh face. Griffith joined the company in 1908 as a writer and actor. Soon, however, the head director of the company, [[Wallace McCutcheon Sr.|Wallace McCutcheon]], fell ill and his son had little success with taking over for him. This led Grifith to become the principal director for the company, and the only director for films made at Biograph between June 1908 and December 1909.<ref>https://www.moma.org/documents/moma_catalogue_3465_300062291.pdf</ref> During these few months, Griffith turned out an exceptional amount of films, with estimates of one 12 minute and one 16 long minute piece per week. The company actually began its venture out West to Hollywood thanks to Griffith's work on ''Ramona'' because he wanted to film on location in Ventura, California.\n\nLongtime friend and colleague of Griffith's [[Billy Bitzer]] worked as the cinematographer for the film. Bitzer was hired originally as an electrician for the Biograph company, but his love of cameras pushed him to become one of cinema's most inventive pioneers. He experimented with photography, especially lighting and close-up shots. The Griffith and Bitzer duo formed shortly after Griffith directed his first film, ''[[The Adventures of Dollie]]'' and continued after both men left the Biograph production company in 1913.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.cobbles.com/simpp_archive/dwgriffith.htm |title=D. W. Griffith\u2014Independent Profile |work=Cobblestone Entertainment |accessdate=October 12, 2019}}</ref> Bitzer's experimental nature is beautifully showcased in the film's sweeping landscape shots of the California mountains and distinct editing techniques like [[cross-cutting]].\n\n==Cast==\n[[File:Mary Pickford cph.3c17995u.jpg|thumb|Mary Pickford, the actress who plays Ramona.]]\n\n*[[Mary Pickford]] as Ramona\n*[[Henry B. Walthall]] as Alessandro\n*[[Francis J. Grandon]] as Felipe\n*[[Kate Bruce]] as The Mother\n*[[W. Chrystie Miller]] as The Priest\n*[[Dorothy Bernard]]\n*[[Gertrude Claire]] as Woman in west\n*[[Robert Harron]]\n*[[Dell Henderson]] as Man at burial\n*[[Mae Marsh]]\n*Frank Opperman as Ranch hand\n*[[Anthony O'Sullivan]] as Ranch hand\n*[[Jack Pickford]] as A boy\n*[[Mack Sennett]] as White exploiter\n\n[[File:Henry B Walthall - Sep 1917 EH.jpg|thumb|Henry B Walthall, the actor who plays Alessandro.]]\n\n==See also==\n* [[List of American films of 1910]]\n* [[D. W. Griffith filmography]]\n* [[Mary Pickford filmography]]\n* [[Ramona (1928 film)]]\n* [[Ramona (1936 film)]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{IMDb title|id=0001371|title=Ramona}}\n* [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=6dO2mBb-_z8 ''Ramona''] on [[YouTube]]\n* {{Internet Archive film|id=Ramona_953|title=Ramona (1910 film)}}\n\n{{D. W. Griffith}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Ramona}}\n[[Category:1910 films]]\n[[Category:1910s drama films]]\n[[Category:1910s short films]]\n[[Category:American films]]\n[[Category:American drama films]]\n[[Category:American silent short films]]\n[[Category:American black-and-white films]]\n[[Category:Films based on American novels]]\n[[Category:Films set in California]]\n[[Category:Films directed by D. W. Griffith]]\n[[Category:Films with screenplays by Stanner E.V. Taylor]]\n[[Category:Films with screenplays by D. W. Griffith]]\n[[Category:Films based on Ramona by Helen Hunt Jackson]]\n[[Category:Articles containing video clips]]\n", "name_user": "Lugnuts", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ramona_(1910_film)"}
